### Describe the bug

It is possible for ClientManager#enableServiceAccount to be called concurrently (for example by TokenEndpoint#processGrantRequest -> TokenEndpoint#clientCredentialsGrant -> ClientManager#enableServiceAccount) this results in duplicate protocol mapper entries

### Version

16.1.1

### Expected behavior

Only three protocol mapper entries are created: Client IP Address, Client Host, Client ID

### Actual behavior

Six protocol mapper entries are created: Client IP Address, Client Host, Client ID, Client IP Address, Client Host, Client ID

### How to Reproduce?

Run Keycloak in a Docker container:
```
docker run --rm --name keycloak -p 8080:8080 -e KEYCLOAK_USER=keycloak -e KEYCLOAK_PASSWORD=keycloak -e KEYCLOAK_LOGLEVEL=DEBUG jboss/keycloak:16.1.1
```

Use the following Java Code to reproduce the behavior:
```java
import org.keycloak.admin.client.KeycloakBuilder;
import org.keycloak.representations.idm.ClientRepresentation;
import org.keycloak.representations.idm.ProtocolMapperRepresentation;

import java.util.Collections;
import java.util.stream.Collectors;

import javax.ws.rs.NotFoundException;

public class Reproducer {

	public static void main(String[] args) throws InterruptedException {
		// Prerequisite:
		// docker run --rm --name keycloak -p 8080:8080 -e KEYCLOAK_USER=keycloak -e KEYCLOAK_PASSWORD=keycloak -e KEYCLOAK_LOGLEVEL=DEBUG jboss/keycloak:16.1.1

		var adminClient = KeycloakBuilder.builder()
				.serverUrl("http://localhost:8080/auth/")
				.clientId("admin-cli")
				.username("keycloak")
				.password("keycloak")
				.realm("master")
				.build();
		var clientsResource = adminClient.realm("master").clients();

		var clientRepresentation = new ClientRepresentation();
		clientRepresentation.setId("reproducer");
		clientRepresentation.setEnabled(true);
		clientRepresentation.setServiceAccountsEnabled(true);
		clientRepresentation.setSecret("very-secret");
		clientRepresentation.setProtocolMappers(Collections.emptyList()); // no protocol mappers defined

		// Clean up previous runs
		try {
			clientsResource.get("reproducer").remove();
		} catch (NotFoundException ex) {
			// ignore
		}

		// At first the client gets created with the default protocol mappers
		clientsResource.create(clientRepresentation);

		// When we update the client the protocol mappers are cleared
		clientsResource.get("reproducer").update(clientRepresentation);

		Runnable doSomethingWithOurReproducerClient = () -> {
			var reproducerClient = KeycloakBuilder.builder()
					.serverUrl("http://localhost:8080/auth/")
					.clientId("reproducer")
					.clientSecret("very-secret")
					.grantType("client_credentials")
					.realm("master")
					.build();

			// Execute a random action
			reproducerClient.tokenManager().grantToken();
		};

		// Do two things in parallel using the "reproducer" client
		var thread1 = new Thread(doSomethingWithOurReproducerClient);
		var thread2 = new Thread(doSomethingWithOurReproducerClient);
		thread1.start();
		thread2.start();
		thread1.join();
		thread2.join();

		// Check
		var mappers = clientsResource.get("reproducer").getProtocolMappers().getMappers();

		if(mappers.size() > 3) {
			System.out.println("Reproducer successful. Protocol mappers: ");
			System.out.println(mappers.stream().map(ProtocolMapperRepresentation::getName).collect(Collectors.joining("\n")));
		} else {
			System.out.println("Reproducer failed");
		}
	}
}
```

Observe the protocol mappers being created twice:
```
13:08:29,935 DEBUG [org.keycloak.protocol.oidc.endpoints.TokenEndpoint] (default task-2) Service account user for client 'reproducer' not found or default protocol mapper for service account not found. Creating now
13:08:29,936 DEBUG [org.keycloak.services.managers.ClientManager] (default task-2) Creating service account protocol mapper 'Client ID' for client 'reproducer'
13:08:29,937 DEBUG [org.keycloak.authentication.ClientAuthenticationFlow] (default task-1) client authenticator SUCCESS: client-secret
13:08:29,937 DEBUG [org.keycloak.authentication.ClientAuthenticationFlow] (default task-1) Client reproducer authenticated by client-secret
13:08:29,937 DEBUG [org.keycloak.services.managers.ClientManager] (default task-2) Creating service account protocol mapper 'Client Host' for client 'reproducer'
13:08:29,937 DEBUG [org.keycloak.services.managers.ClientManager] (default task-2) Creating service account protocol mapper 'Client IP Address' for client 'reproducer'
13:08:29,937 DEBUG [org.keycloak.protocol.oidc.endpoints.TokenEndpoint] (default task-1) Service account user for client 'reproducer' not found or default protocol mapper for service account not found. Creating now
13:08:29,941 DEBUG [org.keycloak.services.managers.ClientManager] (default task-1) Creating service account protocol mapper 'Client ID' for client 'reproducer'
13:08:29,941 DEBUG [org.keycloak.services.managers.ClientManager] (default task-1) Creating service account protocol mapper 'Client Host' for client 'reproducer'
13:08:29,941 DEBUG [org.keycloak.services.managers.ClientManager] (default task-1) Creating service account protocol mapper 'Client IP Address' for client 'reproducer'
```

Observe two entries for each protocol mapper in the UI:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/2938826/155328007-2358a9ca-8d36-4052-8567-0c3e793af7c1.png)


### Anything else?

The presence of these duplicate protocol mapper entries causes some Keycloak REST endpoints to fail due to assumptions that protocol mapper names are unique.

## Possible solution

Mentioned in this comment https://github.com/keycloak/keycloak/issues/10417#issuecomment-2367775925
